-## 6. Rebuilding GNOME OS with your changes and deploying them
+## 7. Rebuilding GNOME OS with your changes and deploying them
 
 While it's possible to rebuild the GNOME OS images on each change and reinstall them each time you make changes, this leads to a very slow iteration cycle and not recommended. Instead, the the systemd-systext and/or systemd-sysupdate workflows described in the following section to build and deploy your changes to your local workstation, VM or a different machine in a much faster way.
 
@@ -128,7 +135,7 @@ ```
 
 Here, `strict: false` avoids rebuilding the whole chain on the next build, and `override-project-caches: true` disables remote cache lookups which, while helpful on the first build, can significantly slow down things on subsequent builds.
 
-### 6.1 Option 1: By building and installing a system extension (`systemd-sysext`)
+### 7.1 Option 1: By building and installing a system extension (`systemd-sysext`)
 
 > This option works best if you want to temporarily and quickly deploy your changes to your local workstation. No reboot is required to see your changes in action. The one component that can't be iterated on with system extensions is the kernel - for that, use the [`systemd-sysupdate` option](#62-option-2-by-building-serving-and-updating-from-a-local-sysupdate-repository-systemd-sysupdate) instead.
 
@@ -165,7 +172,7 @@ $ run0 rm /var/lib/extensions/zz-gnome-control-center.raw
 $ run0 systemd-sysext refresh
 ```
 
-### 6.2 Option 2: By building, serving and updating from a local sysupdate repository (`systemd-sysupdate`)
+### 7.2 Option 2: By building, serving and updating from a local sysupdate repository (`systemd-sysupdate`)
 
 > This option works best if you want to permanently deploy your changes to your local workstation, or if you want to deploy to a VM or a different workstation. A reboot is required to see your changes in action. Unlike with the [`systemd-sysext` option](#61-option-1-by-building-and-installing-a-system-extension-systemd-sysext), this option can be used to iterate on the kernel.
 
@@ -206,7 +213,7 @@ ```shell
